minal article published in 1997, Martin Feldstein developed a framework for calculating the gains in economic welfare that might result from a move from a low level of inflation to full price stability. The present volume extends that analysis, focusing on the likely costs and benefits of achieving price stability not only in the United States, but in Germany, Spain, and the United Kingdom as well. The results show that even small changes in already low inflation rates can have a substantial impact on the economic performance of different countries, and that variations in national tax rules can affect the level of gain from disinflation.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBusiness. 0aInflation (Finance) 0aInflation (Finance)vCongresses. 0aInflation (Finance)xCongresses. 0aInflationxCongrès. 0aMonetary policyvCongresses. 0aMonetary policyxCongresses. 0aMonetary policy. 0aPolitique monétairexCongrès. 0aPrice regulationvCongresses. 0aPrice regulationxCongresses. 0aPrice regulation. 0aPricesxCongressesxGovernment policy. 0aPricesxGovernment policyvCongresses. 0aPrices. 0aPrixxPolitique gouvernementalexCongrès. 0aPrixxRéglementationxCongrès. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aFeldstein, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226241760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226241760.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles